某些學者推測昆蘭古捲屬於"猶太教共同圖書典藏"的說法。 http://www.biblicalarchaeology.org/…/ancient-scribe-links-…/　 Ada Yardeni 得以辨識出那五十件關鍵手抄本出於同一文士的手筆，還要感謝該文士書寫希伯來字母Lamed（ל）時，習慣在起筆時刻意用力造成一個小三角形，落筆時又給予足夠的曲度以構成凹座。這位文士工作的年代，大約在希律王時代（公元前一世紀末葉至公元一世紀初），約當昆蘭團體最昌盛的時期。洞穴內遺留的銅製墨罐則顯示，文士們的確在昆蘭洞穴內書寫並複製這些古代書捲。 換言之，在死海昆蘭洞穴內所保存的古捲，是屬於具有特殊教派氣質的昆蘭團體所獨有。在第二聖殿時期，昆蘭團體屬於相當分化的各種猶太團體中其中一支。昆蘭古捲所呈現的信仰，並不能代表第二聖殿時期主流的猶太教。 >> 昆蘭團體可能參與一世紀猶太羅馬反抗軍 學術界對於昆蘭團體與馬薩達革命軍之間的聯繫所知已久。在昆蘭洞穴與馬薩達的遺物中，都發現昆蘭團體特有的文獻（the liturgical cycle Songs of the Sabbath Sacrifice），那並非主流猶太教所擁有的文獻。 今年（2014）聖經考古學會（Biblical Archaeology Society）發表了《馬薩達（Masada）--死海沙漠要塞》論文集，其中不但詳細摘要了Ada Yardeni的論文重點，同時整理了現代考古學重建羅馬軍團與猶太反抗軍在馬薩達決戰的歷史。 http://www.biblicalarchaeology.org/…/masada-the-dead-seas-…/ 公元66 C.E 猶太人第一次反抗羅馬，成功佔領了耶路撒冷；公元68 C.E. 羅馬人攻陷昆蘭洞穴要塞，70 C.E.羅馬人反攻耶路撒冷成功，拆毀了聖殿，猶太反抗軍撤離耶路撒冷轉進三個沙漠要塞，馬薩達為其中之一。現在許多學者相信，存放在馬薩達牆壁內的文獻，源於逃出昆蘭洞穴要塞之反抗軍。 馬薩達的要塞為天然形成之陡峭壁壘，希律王曾在其上建築工事，反抗軍佔領後繼續支撐羅馬軍團攻勢直到73/74 C.E.，並建造會堂。 羅馬軍團最後以包圍斷絕補給、建築登壁木梯的戰術攻入馬薩達。根據《猶太古史》的作者約瑟夫（Flavius Josephus）報導，猶太反抗軍的領袖Eleazar Ben Yair帶領967位馬薩達戰士中的960位集體自殺，以"自由之身離開這個世界"，避免被羅馬軍人俘虜、奴役與折磨的命運。 >> 對新約研究的可能影響 除了比較昆蘭古捲與其他第二聖殿時期猶太教文獻可能呈現更多此時期猶太教的多元性面貌，進一步改寫E.P.Sanders所謂"共通的猶太教"（common Judaism）的假說。 當代某些針對保羅神學與昆蘭團體之間的比較，也可能因為彼此在歷史上的聯繫性降低而減少實質性的意義。 昆蘭團體與愛色尼（Essenes）派之間可能的關係仍然非常密切。 展開全部帖子Quotes of Early Judaism 猶太文獻選讀 · 2013年4月3日 · Today I found this statement of Apostle Paul in Romans 11:24 very illuminating about how a Jew may become a better Christian-- "For if you [referring to the Gentiles] were cut from what is by nature a wild olive tree, and grafted, contrary to nature, into a cultivated olive tree [referring to the people of God, renewed and transformed in Jesus Christ], how much more will these, the natural branches [referring to the native Jewish people], be grafted back into their own olive ...tree [referring to the people of God, which God promised to renew and transform in Messianic kingdom]."  Paul himself carried a personal real-life story of being cut off because of hardened disbelief and then being re-grafted into the body of Christ because of belief by grace.  Paul own life provides a paradigm for us to understand the dynamics of relationships between the historical Jewish roots of Christianity and the transcendent and surpassing glory of the revelation of the New Testament event in Christian faith. 展開Quotes of Early Judaism 猶太文獻選讀 · 2013年2月26日 · The Qumran idea of purification--true purification comes from the 'spirit of holiness' and true cleansing from the 'humble submission' of the soul to all God's precepts. "For it is through the spirit of true counsel concerning the ways of man that all his sins shall be expiated...He shall be cleansed from all his sins by the spirit of holiness...and his iniquity shall be expiated by the spirit of uprightness and humility. And when his flesh is sprinkled with purifying water and sanctified by cleansing water, it shall be made clean by the humble submission of his soul to all the precepts of God." (I QS III, 6-9) Vermes, The Complete Dead Sea Scrolls in English, 82.Quotes of Early Judaism 猶太文獻選讀 · 2013年2月26日 · The Qumran Community were aware of the danger of pride and never cease to emphasize the sectary's frailty, unworthiness and total dependence on God-- "Clay and dust that I am,       what can I devise unless Thou wish it,       and what contrive unless Thou desire it?... What strength shall I have     unless Thou keep me upright and how shall I understand     unless by (the spirit) which Thou has shaped for me?" (1 QH xviii [formerly x], 5-7) (adapted from Vermes, The Complete Dead Sea Scrolls in English, 73-74) 展開Quotes of Early Judaism 猶太文獻選讀 · 2013年2月26日 · 2 Maccabbees describes the situation of Hellenizing program in Judea during Antiochus IV Epiphanes (175-164 BCE)- "So Hellenism reached a high point with the introduction of foreign customs through the boundless wickedness of the impious Jason, no true High Priest. As a result, the priests no longer had any enthusiasm for their duties at the altar, but despised the temple and neglected the sacrifices; and in defiance of the law they eagerly contributed to the expenses of the wrestling-school whenever the opening gong called them. They placed no value on their hereditary dignities, but cared above everything for Hellenic honours." (2 Mac. iv, 13-15)Quotes of Early Judaism 猶太文獻選讀 · 2013年2月26日 · After travelling through Vermes' The Complete Dead Sea Scrolls in English, the alleged "scribal creative freedom" as claimed by Vermes, in my impression, is at best limited to the Qumran Community as a part of the sectarian practice. But Vermes might be correct about the "variegated Judaism" in the inter-Testamental era.Quotes of Early Judaism 猶太文獻選讀 · 2013年2月2日 · I am curious about the validity of Geza Vernes' claim about the greatest novelty of Qumran community:  "The Dead Sea Scrolls have afforded for the first time direct insight into the creative literary-religious process at work within that variegated Judaism which flourished during the last two centuries of quasi-national independence, before the catastrophe of 70 CE forced the rabbinic successors of the Pharisees to attempt to create an 'orthodoxy' by reducing dangerous multiplicity to a simple, tidy and easily controllable unity." ~Gaza Vermes, The Complete Dead Sea Scrolls in English, revised edition, 23-24Quotes of Early Judaism 猶太文獻選讀 · 2012年12月5日 · “The Pseudepigrapha, therefore, are an important source for understanding the social dimensions of Early Judaism (xxix).”  (Charlesworth, J. The Old Testament Pseudepigrapha. Vol 1.)Quotes of Early Judaism 猶太文獻選讀 · 2012年12月5日 · REVIEW AND CRITIQUE Shaye J. D. Cohen, S. From the Maccabees to the Mishnah, 2nd ed., 2006 In From the Maccabees to the Mishnah (2nd ed., 2006), Cohen a contemporary Jewish scholar teaching at Harvard gives the most concise account of the three-hundred-and-fifty years of history of Judaism from the Maccabbees to Mishnah. This work is significant to Christian biblical scholarship because Cohen in his research and presentation completely stands away from the current debate rega...展開Quotes of Early Judaism 猶太文獻選讀 · 2012年12月5日 · "...the three themes of the Shema are the Kingship of God, Reward and Punishment, and Redemption...by virtue of its central place in the liturgy, serves well as a convenient outline of Jewish beliefs (76)." (Shaye J. D. Cohen, S. From the Maccabees to the Mishnah, 2nd ed., 2006)Quotes of Early Judaism 猶太文獻選讀 · 2012年12月5日 · "Ezekiel claims that every person receives his or her just deserts from God.  The author of Chronicles, a work of the Persian or early Hellenistic period, implemented this theory in his revision of the book of Kings. The Deuteronomic historian was satisfied with the doctrine of corporate responsibility, but the Chronicler was not (85)." (Shaye J. D. Cohen, S. From the Maccabees to the Mishnah, 2nd ed., 2006)Quotes of Early Judaism 猶太文獻選讀 · 2012年12月5日 · "We may be sure that the vast majority of ancient Jews believed in God, circumcised their sons on the eighth day of life, abstained from pork, did not work on the Sabbath, avoided any association with idolatry (such as sacrifices to "idols" or the emperor), prayed to God, venerated the Torah, honored the temple of Jerusalem, and so on. All of this may be true and accurate, but it does not tell us anything about Jewish religiosity and spirituality.......Whether Jewish piety lends itself more readily than the Christian to a focus on external observances rather than inner spirituality is a question that a historian cannot answer (69)."  (Shaye J. D. Cohen, S. From the Maccabees to the Mishnah, 2nd ed., 2006)Quotes of Early Judaism 猶太文獻選讀 · 2012年12月5日 · "It is perhaps not surprising that outsiders saw the Jews as a single people or ethnic group. Outsiders seldom see the disagreements, tensions, and rivalries that are so apparent to insiders. It is perhaps more surprising that the Jews of antiquity, in some contexts at least, saw themselves as citizens of one nation and one religion, unaware of, or oblivious to, the fact that they were separated from each other by their diverse languages, practices, ideologies, and political loyalties. But in fact, for all of their disagreements and rivalries, ancient Jews were united by a common set of practices and beliefs that characterized virtually all segments of Jewry...This common Judaism was the unity within the diversity (14)." (Shaye J. D. Cohen, S. From the Maccabees to the Mishnah, 2nd ed., 2006)Quotes of Early Judaism 猶太文獻選讀 · 2012年12月5日 · "Preexilic Israel and Second Temple Judaism also differed in their understanding of theodicy, God's administration of justice...Preexilic Israel believed that God administered justice in this world. The righteous and the wicked were not always the direct recipients of God;s attentions, because God could reward or punish their offspring in their stead (emphasis on the collective). Second Temple Judaism insisted that God punishes and rewards only those who deserve it, and that ...the conduct of one's ancestors is irrelevant (emphasis on the individual). Since God does not always seem to set matters right in this world, he must do so in the next. Second Temple Judaism therefore elaborated complex schemes included the resurrection of the dead. Just as God will reestablish justice for the individual, he shall do so for the nation by destroying the yoke of the nations and restoring the sovereignty of the people of Israel. Jerusalem and the temple will be restored to their former glory and God's annointed one (messiah) shall reign securely, All of these eschatological doctrines....are innovations of Second Temple Judaism (10)." (Shaye J. D. Cohen, S. From the Maccabees to the Mishnah) 展開Quotes of Early Judaism 猶太文獻選讀 · 2012年12月5日 · Shaye J. D. Cohen (born October 21, 1948) is the Littauer Professor of Hebrew Literature and Philosophy in the Department of Near Eastern Languages and Civilizations of Harvard University. He received his Ph.D. in Ancient History, with distinction, from Columbia University in 1975. He is also an ordained rabbi, and for many years was the Dean of the Graduate School and Shenkman Professor of Jewish History at the Jewish Theological Seminary in New York. Before arriving at Harv...ard in July 2001, he was for ten years the Samuel Ungerleider Professor of Judaic Studies and Professor of Religious Studies at Brown University. The focus of Cohen's research is the boundary between Jews and gentiles and between Judaism and its surrounding culture. He is also a published authority on Jewish reactions to Hellenism and to Christianity. Cohen has received several honors for his work, including an honorary doctorate from the Jewish Theological Seminary and various fellowships. He has been honored by appointment as Croghan Distinguished Visiting Professor of Religion (Williams College), the Louis Jacobs Lecturer (Oxford University), the David M. Lewis Lecturer (Oxford University), Lady Davis Fellowship (Visiting Professor) of Jewish History (Hebrew University of Jerusalem), the Block Lecturer (Indiana University), the Roland Visiting Lecturer (Stanford University) and the Pritchett Lecturer (University of California, Berkeley). He appeared on a Nova episode [1] as an expert on Jewish history. He also appears in PBS's Jesus to Christ Documentary. [2] Cohen has published many essays, co-authored many books, and written a number of books individually, including: "Josephus in Galilee and Rome: His Vita and Development As a Historian" (1979), "From the Maccabees to the Mishnah" (1988), "The Beginnings of Jewishness: Boundaries, Varieties, Uncertainties" (2001), "Why Aren't Jewish Women Circumcised?: Gender and Covenant in Judaism" (2005) and "The Significance of Yavneh and Other Essays in Jewish Hellenism" (2010)[3]. Wikipedia, accessed 2012/12/5 展開Quotes of Early Judaism 猶太文獻選讀 · 2012年12月5日 · Both Josephus and Philo of the first century had hardly said anything about Jewish eschatology. I wonder why today’s study of Jewish eschatology does not discuss the reason why there are such kind of significant missing of eschatology in their works, if the “intensified eschatological expectation” was indeed the common characteristic of early Judaism in the first-century, as N.T. Wright has proposed.更多




















